         <abstract>
            <p>Consider the Cauchy principal value integral $$I(kf; \lambda) = \not{\int}^1_{-1} k(x) \frac{f(x)}{x - \lambda} dx,\quad -1 &lt; \lambda &lt; 1.$$ If we approximate $f(x)$ by $\sum^N_{j = 0}a_jp_j(x; w)$ where $\{p_j\}$ is a sequence of orthonormal polynomials with respect to an admissible weight function $w$ and $a_j = (f, p_j)$, then an approximation to $I(kf; \lambda)$ is given by $\sum^N_{j = 0}a_jI(kp_j; \lambda)$. If, in turn, we approximate $a_j$ by $a_{jm} = \sum^m_{i = 1}w_{im}f(x_{im})p_j(x_{im})$, then we get a double sequence of approximations $\{Q^N_m(f; \lambda)\}$ to $I(kf; \lambda)$. We study the convergence of this sequence by relating it to the sequence of approximations associated with $I(wf; \lambda)$ which has been investigated previously.</p>
          </abstract>
